        <comment>
  <id>47023589</id>
  <body><![CDATA[Brwown spent a year researching, a year writing, and I wasn't surprised at all to learn that, since it's obvious the book asked for many research concerning descriptions of places, paintings, plus many other things. <br /><br />Also, Brown begins by stating 3 "facts". The first one is a mistake on his part. The Priory of Sion never existed, the documents, once thought real though, were actually forged (by Plantard as you mentioned it). But, I must say that before the DVC, not that many people talked about this, and I can forgive him his mistake. The sources about it can be very misleading.<br /><br />The second fact is that the Opus Dei exists, that it's a Vatican prelature and has a headquarter in NY (again, if I remember correctly, it could be some place else). That fact is correct.<br /><br />The third fact is that the descriptions of places, artworks, etc. are accurate, which is exact also.<br /><br />The book is obviously fiction, he never pretended otherwise, but with some real elements, that he shaped into something else (his plot).<br />Just like when you read the Deverry saga (Katharine Kerr) or The Deryni saga (Katherine Kurtz), it's obviously fantasy, but with many historical elements reinvented in it.<br /><br />It seems many people dislike when an author does that, they say it's misleading. Just like you said it, and I know other people who say the same, but not especially concerning the DVC, concerning many different books that include historical elements. They see the elements as distorted, when I, and I'm not the only one, see a clever reinvention of facts to serve a fiction plot.<br /><br />"He wrote this book and pretended it was a history book."<br />Where did he pretend such? Not in the book anyway. Because he presented certain elements as facts in the beginning in NO way means he claimed it as non-fiction. <br /><br />You end your review with "I've already done more legitimate historical research on this review than Brown did in his whole book".<br />I find these types of comment particularly arrogant. For my part, I can see in the book all the research it demanded, on many details. To say you did as much research for your review is ridiculous, and I keep wondering what rubs people so wrong to write stuff like that. <br />It sounds like every hater of this book could have written better in no time...]]></body>
  
