  <body><![CDATA[<i>"Brwown spent a year researching, a year writing, and I wasn't surprised at all to learn that, since it's obvious the book asked for many research concerning descriptions of places, paintings, plus many other things."</i><br /><br />Then he should have put in a bibliography.<br /><br /><i>"I must say that before the DVC, not that many people talked about this, and I can forgive him his mistake."</i><br /><br />If Brown researched for a year on the subject without discovering it was a hoax, that seems like a major failure of his research faculties, especially since a similar earlier book that dealt with the priory, <i>Holy Blood and the Holy Grail</i> had been publically discredited by scholars as early as the seventies.<br /><br /><i>"The third fact is that the descriptions of places, artworks, etc. are accurate, which is exact also."</i><br /><br />Actually, as Brown is not an art historian or architectural historian, many of his facts about art and particularly symbolic analysis are highly inaccurate and do not correspond to any modern or historical interpretations.<br /><br /><i>"The book is obviously fiction, he never pretended otherwise, but with some real elements . . "</i><br /><br />I have no problem with an author using realistic elements when they do it correctly. An author who claims that their work is correct and then writes a book full of errors is another matter. It's like a fake autobiography or tell-all book: it makes people less informed and it spreads unsubstantiated claims.<br /><br /><i>"Where did he pretend [that it was a history book]"</i><br /><br />When he claimed in the beginning that the facts he was presenting were true.<br /><br /><i>"To say you did as much research for your review is ridiculous"</i><br /><br />I didn't say I had done more research, just more legitimate research.<br /><br /><i>"I keep wondering what rubs people so wrong to write stuff like that."</i><br /><br />You wonder what rubs people wrong about a book which is full of misinformation presented as fact? I would have thought that would be pretty clear.]]></body>
  
