  <id>47092495</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>"Then he should have put in a bibliography."</i><br /><br />... Generally, fiction books don't include bibliographies. I've read fiction books about the celtic culture or about the middle ages or about other historical periods, and the authors read a lot and researched the subject, but they didn't include a bibliography either.<br /><br />Fiction books are not supposed to have bibliographies even when there were research to write them. <br /><br /><i>"If Brown researched for a year on the subject without discovering it was a hoax, that seems like a major failure"</i><br /><br />I agree that's a pity. But everyone can do mistakes, and he didn't spend a year just researching the Priory, but many other things.<br /><br /><i>"many of his facts about art and particularly symbolic analysis are highly inaccurate and do not correspond to any modern or historical interpretations."</i><br /><br />?? He said that his <b>descriptions</b> were facts. He never said his analysis or interpretations were, for anyway they completely belong to his plot, which is fiction.<br /><br /><i>"When he claimed in the beginning that the facts he was presenting were true."</i><br /><br />Oh my, you really have an understanding problem O_o<br />He said there were THREE facts, he didn't say the whole book was fact. <br />The 3 facts being the existence of a Priory of Sion (which is a mistake as we already said) - note that he didn't say the Priory did the same stuff as in the book, just that it existed; the existence of a Vatican prelature named Opus Dei - and he didn't write either that they really have crazy assassin monks among them; finally the accuracy of the descriptions (not the interpretations) of artworks and places.<br /><br />Maybe Dan Brown said elsewhere he thought his book was history? I don't know. But you are incredibly ridiculous when you say "he claimed the facts are true in the beginning".<br />He did no such thing. He claimed there were 3 facts.]]></body>
  
