        <comment>
  <id>47307739</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>"Fiction books are not supposed to have bibliographies even when there were research to write them."</i><br /><br />Most fiction books also don't start with a claim of the accuracy of their details and claims. I have also read a number of fiction books which provided bibliographies for the factual items the author presents.<br /><br /><i>"He claimed there were 3 facts."</i><br /><br />These 'three facts' were rather broad claims, and none of them have actually turned out to be true. The Priory of Sion was a hoax, Opus Dei is not a 'sect' as Brown claims, as it is a primarily lay organization and has no monks as depicted in the book, and as for the last fact, his descriptions are simply not factual. For a few examples:<br /><br />He claims that more than eighty gospels were considered for inclusion in the New Testament, when there is evidence for no more than two dozen. He claims the divinity of Christ was not established until the time of Constantine, when earlier texts already refer to belief in divinity. Brown also claims that the Dead Sea Scrolls give evidence of gospels which were suppressed by Constantine, when they are actually all Old Testament documents and contain nothing about the life of Christ.<br /><br />His claim about the 'three facts' is clearly meant to lend credulity to his story, to convince us that even if he is writing fiction, he is writing about real ideas. This is simply not true.<br /><br />In addition, it is difficult to mark precisely where his claim of fact ends and his fiction is supposed to begin. Is the inclusion of an 'Opus Dei monk' supposed to be a factual representation of the organization, or a fiction? Why did he make the claim about the 'three facts' in the first place if most of his descriptions are errors shading into pure fiction?]]></body>
  
