        <comment>
  <id>47340817</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>"Why did he make the claim about the 'three facts' in the first place if most of his descriptions are errors shading into pure fiction?"</i><br /><br />Well, I believe there's obviously a commercial purpose: this page "Facts" contributes to a controversy, since as you say there is no exact line given to separate facts from fiction. <br /><br />But I also think Brown was actually misled and believed the Priory existed, since I know many sources can be misleading. I don't think he knew it was fake when he wrote his book.<br /><br />Concerning the Opus Dei, I don't think he ever thought they had assassins... This is obviously part of the thriller plot and anyone in their right mind would also come to that conclusion. But the corporal mortifications are real and recognized by the organization. One of the 2 main meanings of a "sect" being an organization with different rules/beliefs than the larger picture to which it belongs, it's not <i>that</i> wrong to call the Opus Dei as such.<br /><br />I also want to add that despite the page "facts", the DVC is still published in fiction. <br />I guess this is why I don't have a problem with the half-truths, as you put it, of Brown's novel. I've already seen non fiction books containing crazier ideas... The DVC at least remains part of fiction.]]></body>
  
