        <comment>
  <id>47367549</id>
  <body><![CDATA[<i>"I also think Brown was actually misled and believed the Priory existed, since I know many sources can be misleading. I don't think he knew it was fake when he wrote his book."</i><br /><br />It certainly could be true--but that just means that Brown is bad at research and overly confident. He naively made a claim he couldn't deliver on, and whether he did it because he was ignorant or because he was deliberately trying to mislead people to create controversy, both are signs of a bad author.<br /><br /><i>". . . a "sect" being an organization with different rules/beliefs than the larger picture to which it belongs, it's not that wrong to call the Opus Dei as such."</i><br /><br />From what I've read, Opus Dei is pretty well in-line with the standard Catholic teachings--it is a central group of a church, not a group which has broken off or which entertains controversial beliefs.<br /><br /><i>"I also want to add that despite the page "facts", the DVC is still published in fiction."</i><br /><br />It's true, but even without a claim of 'representing true facts', a work of fiction can still be criticized for being unrealistic. Authors try to create 'verisimilitude' which helps the audience to suspend their disbelief and get lost in the story. If they write things that don't make sense, it makes the story worse.<br /><br />If we read a story which is realistic (not fantasy) and a character survives a direct nuclear blast by using an umbrella, that is going to seem silly and won't make sense in the story. If an author claims the Catholic church was started by Martin Luther, that will make the story nonsensical.<br /><br />The problem with these sorts of errors is that the author chooses what they want to put into a book. They choose the level of detail that they include. If they try to put in realistic details but fail, then that is bad writing. A good author knows their limits. The claim about 'facts' just makes it worse, because it shows that despite his attempts to research and use details, Brown still wrote a book that was fundamentally inaccurate.]]></body>
  
