  <body><![CDATA[<i>Keely wrote: ""Brwown spent a year researching, a year writing, and I wasn't surprised at all to learn that, since it's obvious the book asked for many research concerning descriptions of places, paintings, plus..."</i> Herman Wouk spent 20 years researching Winds of War/War and Remembrance. Should he have included a bibliography? I say no because much that we know about The Shoah has changed. For instance, in Remembrance, it says that 1 million people were killed in a single day at Auschwitz-Birkenau. We now know the most killed in a single day was closer to 40k, with the total being 1.1 million. But in the 1950s and 1960s, when Wouk was doing his research, all of the material said it the total killed in Birkenau was closer to 4 million. <br /><br />Also, Wouk read close to 400 books for those two books. Aside from Crichton, I cannot think of a single writer fiction writer who includes a bibliography for their research. Most fiction readers don't care.]]></body>
  
