        <comment>
  <id>61766519</id>
  <body><![CDATA[Yes, most fiction readers don't care, which is why authors can get away with passing off fraud as truth. I'm sure the majority of listeners of talk radio pundits also don't care about accuracy or sources, but ignoring those is still bad journalism.<br /><br />Any time someone claims they are being accurate to facts and to truth, they should provide sources, no matter where those books happen to be shelved in the bookstore. I'm not saying a writer can't make a piece of fiction full of ridiculous conspiracies--I enjoyed the Illuminatus! trilogy well enough, after all--I'm just saying that when an author starts to claim the accuracy of their facts, they have started to play very freely with the definition of 'fiction'.<br /><br />And yeah, why shouldn't Wouk have included a bibliography to show where he got his information from? Why would it make a difference that our understanding of the subject has changed since he wrote it? Are you suggesting we should just not bother using sources because someday, we might have a different perspective? That seems rather backwards, to me.<br /><br />And it is true that most fiction authors don't use bibliographies, but that's because most fiction doesn't require it. You don't have to provide textual support for a story you made up, because you made it up. Boo Radley and Scout aren't real people, so there are no facts to check about whether the author accurately represented them.]]></body>
  
