  <id>61782303</id>
  <body><![CDATA[If readers wished to know about Brown's research, he even includes some of the titles in the text. Or if they want a more in-depth list, and they have internet access, they can go here: <a target="_blank" href="http://www.danbrown.com/html/novels/davinci_code/bibliography.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.danbrown.com/html/novels/d...</a><br /><br />As for why Wouk didn't, between Winds and Remembrance, the story is nearly 3,000 pages. Throw on another 30-60 pages for the bibliography and it's unnecessary padding. The story is characters and what they went through not his research. Crichton used bibliographies, and many times (such as with Eaters of the Dead, Congo, and The Andromeda Strain) he used a mix of real and fictional references.<br /><br />I wouldn't suggest to anyone not to use sources. In fact, I'm currently in the middle of writing a novel that has taken me 11 years to research. I don't plan on including a bibliography because those interested in the subject will, no doubt, find the resources themselves--or some similar to what I read. However, I have everything documented so that I can easily reference something should I need to.]]></body>
  
