        <comment>
  <id>95022779</id>
  <body><![CDATA[The truth, Keely, is that you're more experienced than the average reader. To borrow an analogy of yours that I quite like: when you've been exposed to certain flavours enough times, you get tired of those flavours, as much as you might have liked them to begin with. Then when another cook comes along and everyone claims that their work tastes divine, you know better than to take their word straight off, since you can tell real vanilla and chocolate from the artificial stuff. The average person might not be able to, or want to be able to.<br /><br />Dan Brown's work was probably the first example, for me, of an overused flavour tasting artificial despite the hype generated by others around me. Langdon is pretty 2D, and he often feels Mary-Sue-ish*. The plot of The Da Vinci Code mirrors too much of Angels and Demons - as well as every other Langdon book by Brown - from the pacing, to the characters, down to the very plot structures. As an example:<br />- Langdon is introduced as an intellectual much admired by everyone, students and exotic women alike, and doesn't carry any major character flaws (claustrophobia dosen't count)<br />- There is an exotic woman, and she will be well-figured and involved intimately with what the evildoers want, somehow (antimatter, bloodline of Christ, etc.). Also, she will only figure prominently in the book she appears in, and disappear for some reason or another in the sequels.<br />- The evildoers operate primarily through one man, who is invariably endowed with superhuman endurance, a strange name and a "stranger appearance" (albinos, bodies covered in tattoos, and, of course, a person of Middle Eastern descent)<br />- Secret societies who apparently leave signs of their existence everywhere, so long as one with the "right training and mind" could see it. Which are none of Langdon's students, if I remember right. You can't walk to the corner store without bypassing half a dozen secret societies, apparently, especially not in Italy.<br /><br />I could go on, but it would be a waste of time. I think I got my point across. Brown has found his formula, and that is what he is comfortable working within. He does not experiment. He does not go outside of his comfort zone. I, for one, can't read any more of his books. I'm not zombified enough for that, thanks. Your review has basically taken the words out of my mouth, but made eloquent. It was a pleasure to read.<br /><br />*Brown actually admits to purposely making Langdon this, according to Wikipedia: <a target="_blank" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Langdon" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_L...</a>]]></body>
  
